                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I was recently promoted.  My previous job had me as a supervisor of about 8 people, and now I am working purely on change control and system administration.  I am still under the same boss.  
<br />

<br />
The boss in question recently gave me a part-time assistant, since the person who previously held this position let the system administration go right to hell and there's a ton of work to be done.  The assistant is one of the people I used to supervise.  She and I have always gotten along fairly well and so that's worked out well.
<br />

<br />
Here's the problem.  About 3 or 4 months ago, my boss started to get very friendly with this girl who is now my assistant.  She managed to wring a bunch of promises out of him about things he'd do for her in the work place - training, new hours, better duties, etc.  She seemed smug about this at the time.  Now, she's singing a different song.  It's a textbook case of sexual harassment.  He calls her all the time, both at work and at home.  If she isn't at her desk when he calls, he screams at her and demands to know where she was and who she was talking to.  He shares information with her and no one else - but if anyone else happens to know that info, no matter how they got it, he freaks on her.  She sits at her desk pale and frightened, unable to concentrate on anything - including the work I give her.
<br />

<br />
Yesterday, she was very sick and went home early.  Our boss is off on Mondays.  However, he still called her desk repeatedly and then called her new supervisor, the guy who replaced me in my old job, to find out where the hell she was.  Then he called her at home.  She called here to talk to her supervisor.  He wasn't here, so I talked to her and she was utterly flustered and sounded near tears.  
<br />

<br />
So... how to proceed?  Part of me doesn't feel all that sorry for her - she was pretty smug about being his pet for awhile and that was pretty annoying.  But she's having a real issue now and isn't dealing with it well.  Plus, it makes it a rather hostile workplace for everyone else as everybody knows what's going on.  Another bad thing is that the manager directly above my boss is his best friend.  Can't talk to him.  
<br />

<br />
So... what to do you think?  Any input is appreciated.
<br />

<br />
--Masuri</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
