                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Well, may sound strange coming from me. However, in this case I'm kinda leaning on .. you made your bed, now lay in it. 
<br />

<br />
Sounds like it's not so much sexual harassment, but a relationship with a control freak. The boss is a scum bag yes, however a person can't flirt with flames then say sexual harassment if they get burned later. Just too much, "It's everyone elses fault, not mine" going around these days.
<br />

<br />
My advice to this person would be to put her foot down. No, not use sexual harassment as a form of sheilding herself. Those rules are for people who really need them and when used inappropriately trivializes it for them. But to tell him to stop the behavior, it's not wanted, and if it continues she go to his boss. But she will have to be honest about the nature of their relationship and take responsiblity for her part.
<br />

<br />
If that doesn't work, then maybe she needs to just get a new job. She doesnt HAVE to stay there. Seems to me the people most victimized by this are the people around them like you and other co-workers.
<br />

<br />
You didn't reap any benefits of their "thing" yet you have to deal with the garbage it created. Hell, seems to me you're the one who could file a complaint. "This isn't my mess, but I am being affected. Tell these two to knock it off so I can get my job done"
<br />

<br />
Hopefully this woman learned a very important lesson!</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="text-decoration: underline">Quote of the Week:</span> 
