                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Yikes. You guys just scared me there. Regardless of whether she and the boss has a flaming affair, flirted a lot, flirted a little,  or whether it was harmless banter on her part or not, a person in the position of authority cannot act like that at work. From what was described here, his behavior is harrassment whether or not she 'deserves' it for using his attention to garner favors. Once either of the parties indicated they were uncomfortable with the others behavior, that's when it crosses the line into harrassment. It doesn't have to be sexual either, if he is creating a hostile work environment that's sufficient as far as most company's policies are concerned (at least in California?). As for his boss being friends with him, take it to him anyway and if he has any sense of self-preservation he'll take it up with his friend and make it stop. No one deserves to be treated like that at work. No one. 
<br />

<br />
I will also jump on the bandwagon and say take it to your HR department if you haven't already.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
